vations project 1 develops practical methods of sex and gender analysis for scientists and engineers 2 provides case studies as concrete illustrations of how sex and gender analysis leads to innovation it is crucially important to identify gender bias and understand how it operates in science and technology but analysis cannot stop there analyzing sex and gender prospectively can serve as a resource to stimulate new knowledge and technologies from the start sex and gender analyses act as controls or filters for bias providing critical rigor in science medicine and engineering research policy and practice the gendered innovations project was initiated at the clayman institute at stanford july 2009 the project entered into a collaboration with the european union january 2011 in addition to drawing experts from across the us gendered innovations now has access to experts from the eu 27 member states donate make a donation social links facebook twitter youtube scribd contact serra house 589 capistrano way stanford ca 94305 8640 map 650 723 1994 gender email stanford edu
